context: Two aspects of indigenous pre-Hispanic culture that withstood time are <a0_0><b3_0><b5_0>chenchule'<b5_0/><b3_0/> and <b4_0><b7_0>inafa'maolek<b7_0/><b4_0/><a0_0/><a1_0>. Chenchule<a1_0/>' is the intricate system of reciprocity at the heart of Chamorro society. It is rooted in the core value of inafa'maolek. Historian Lawrence Cunningham in <b6_0>1992<b6_0/> wrote, "In a Chamorro sense, <a2_0>the land and its produce belong to everyone<a2_0/>. Inafa'maolek, or interdependence, is the key, or central value, in Chamorro culture ... Inafa'maolek depends on a spirit of cooperation and sharing. This is the armature, or core, that everything in Chamorro culture revolves around. It is a powerful concern for mutuality rather than individualism and private property rights."
